snippet.textDisplay: To be honest its too early to tell but On paper, it looks like Xbox Series X is technically the more impressive next-gen console. From my perspective we don't buy video game consoles worrying about their specs but in fact balance of variety of spectacular games and performance does matter.

They have so many custom parts in order to optimize their system for speed, that i dont think it will actually be that much less "powerful" than the xbox. Yeah, seems like PS5 in the winner for me here. Itll hurt my pockets less :p

Yeah, seems like PS5 in the winner for me here. Itll hurt my pockets less :p

snippet.textDisplay:
Great video, really nice break down of it all.

My question probably requires a crystal ball and some tarot cards to get the answer but I think worth discussing.

In my view, the Sony reveal seems like an odd way to do it pushing the hardware extra hard to get that performance. They are also demanding a hell of a lot from their SSD to the point where nothing comparable is on the market and there is no guarantee will be this year.

This to me potentially sounds like a recipe for disaster. Hardware clocked faster has a higher failure rate, NVME SSDs also produce large amounts of heat and that causes them to throttle back in speed and even fail. This is especially pertinent for the expanded storage which will also require cooling.

Do you think with all this in mind that there is a danger of high failure rates with PS5?
